Disaggregation of hardware resources and integration of heterogeneous accelerators are two emerging trends in datacenters. Existing data systems focus on either disaggregated systems with homogeneous CPU processors or incorporation of heterogeneous accelerators within traditional monolithic servers. None can adequately address the challenges posed by systems that are both disaggregated and heterogeneous. We present DHAP, an end-to-end framework comprising a query compiler and a specialized runtime, designed to efficiently process online analytical queries in a disaggregated and heterogeneous environment. At higher levels of our compiler, a planning module automatically identifies an efficient execution plan. At lower levels, various optimizations are applied to generate executable code that is tailored for heterogeneous back-ends. The underlying runtime efficiently processes queries on disaggregated CPU and GPU compute nodes, facilitating inter-stage pipelined execution, minimizing communication costs, and meeting the local memory capacity constraints of compute nodes. Experimental results show that DHAP achieves near-optimal solutions, with latency speedups of up to 16.3 × on SSB and TPC benchmarks. Furthermore, it attains 2.8 × and 13.9 × end-to-end latency speedups compared to a disaggregated query processing system and a GPU-accelerated distributed data processing framework, respectively. The code of DHAP is available at https://github.com/sjtu-zhao-lab/DHAP.